		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 72pt;text-indent: -72pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Item </font><font style="display: inline;">2</font><font style="display: inline;">.0</font><font style="display: inline;">2</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">Results of Operations and Financial Condition</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;text-indent:74pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">On</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">November 3</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> 20</font><font style="display: inline;">14</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Frontier Communications Corporation (&#x201C;Frontier&#x201D; or the &#x201C;Company&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;"> issued a press release.&nbsp;&nbsp;A copy</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;o</font><font style="display: inline;">f the press release is attached hereto as Exhibit 99.</font><font style="display: inline;">1</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>

			<font style="display: inline;">The information </font><font style="display: inline;">furnished </font><font style="display: inline;">in </font><font style="display: inline;">Item 2.02 of </font><font style="display: inline;">this Form 8-K and </font><font style="display: inline;">in </font><font style="display: inline;">Exhibit 99.1 attached hereto</font><font style="display: inline;"> shall not be deemed &#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;">filed</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x201D; for purposes </font><font style="display: inline;">of Section 18 of the</font><font style="display: inline;"> Securities and Exchange </font><font style="display: inline;">Act of 1934 </font><font style="display: inline;">(the &#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;">Exchange Act</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x201D;</font><font style="display: inline;">) or</font><font style="display: inline;"> otherwise </font><font style="display: inline;">subject to th</font><font style="display: inline;">e liabilities of that section, </font><font style="display: inline;">nor shall</font><font style="display: inline;"> it be deemed incorporated by </font><font style="display: inline;">reference in any filing under the</font><font style="display: inline;"> Securities </font><font style="display: inline;">Ac</font><font style="display: inline;">t of 1933 (the &#x201C;Securities Act&#x201D;) or the Exchange Act, </font><font style="display: inline;">except as expressly</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">set forth by specific reference in such a filing.</font>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Stamford, Conn., </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">November </font><font $</font><font style="display: inline;">1,140.9</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, operating income of $</font><font style="display: inline;">197.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and</font><font style="display: inline;"> net income attributable to common shareholders of $</font><font style="display: inline;">42.0 </font><font style="display: inline;">million, $</font><font style="display: inline;">7.5 </font><font style="display: inline;">million</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">and severance costs of 			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">We are very pleased to have achieved sequential growth both in residential and in business </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">customer </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">revenue in the third quarter,&#x201D; said Maggie Wilderotter, Chairman and CEO.&nbsp; &#x201C;This represents </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">continuing progress</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> in our objective of improving our revenue trajectory.&nbsp; We also delivered our seventh consecutive quarter of strong broadband net additions, with market share improvements in 81% of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">local </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">markets year-to-date.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">In addition, today we announced an expansion of our strategic partnership with Intuit to provide premium tech customer support to their small business customers and accountants who use QuickBooks&#xAE; Online, QuickBooks&#xAE; desktop, Payments and Payroll products.&nbsp;&nbsp;Finally, our &#x201C;America&#x2019;s Best Communities&#x201D; prize contest launched this quarter with DISH Networks and CoBank as our key partners, providing small communities in the Frontier footprint the opportunity to win up to $3 million for submitting and implementing a strong economic development and improved lifestyle plan. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">With this momentum, combined with the potential we have in our newly-acquired Connecticut markets, we are extremely well positioned to achieve our long-term objectives of revenue growth, delivering strong free cash flow, and maintaining a very attractive dividend payout ratio.&#x201D;&nbsp; </font>
		</p>

The Company also </font><font style="display: inline;">incurred $</font><font style="display: inline;">40.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> in capital expenditures during the </font><font style="display: inline;">third</font><font style="display: inline;"> quarter of 2014 </font><font style="display: inline;">and $82.3 million for the first nine months of 2014 </font><font style="display: inline;">related to integration activities in connection with the AT&amp;T Connecticut transaction.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">T</font><font style="display: inline;">he Company also </font><font style="display: inline;">used $</font><font style="display: inline;">16.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> of</font><font style="display: inline;"> the previously r</font><font style="display: inline;">eceived Connect America Fund </font><font style="display: inline;">funding</font><font style="display: inline;"> in the third quarter of 2014 and $40.9 million during the first nine months of 2014 </font><font style="display: inline;">as </font><font style="display: inline;">compared to $</font><font style="display: inline;">11.8</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">million in the </font><font style="display: inline;">third</font><font style="display: inline;"> quarter of 2013</font><font style="display: inline;"> and $21.0 million duri</font><font style="display: inline;">ng the first nine months of 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Op</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">erating cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">was $</font><font style="display: inline;">457.9</font><font style="display: inline;"> million for the </font><font style="display: inline;">third</font><font style="display: inline;"> quarter of 201</font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;"> resulting in an operating cash flow margin of </font><font style="display: inline;">40.1</font><font style="display: inline;">%</font><font style="display: inline;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Operating cash flow, </font><font style="display: inline;">as adjusted and defined by the Company in the attached Schedule A, was</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;$</font><font style="display: inline;">479.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, or </font><font style="display: inline;">42.0</font><font style="display: inline;">%, after excluding </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">41.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of acquis</font><font style="display: inline;">ition and integration costs and </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">0.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of severance costs</font><font style="display: inline;">, partially offset by $</font><font style="display: inline;">20.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">of cash pension contributions/OPEB payments in excess of</font><font style="display: inline;"> pension and other postretirement benefit </font><font style="display: inline;">expense</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 12pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:12pt;">Working Capital</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">At </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">September</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> 30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">the Company</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> had a working capital surplus of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">$</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">1,589.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">which includes </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">restricted cash of $1,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">19.0 m</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">illion resulting from the net proceeds of the debt financing described below and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">the classification of certain debt maturing in the </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">first </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">nine months</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> of 2015</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">$</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">247.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> as a current liability</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> Excluding such restricted cash, our working capital surplus was $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">70.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> million at September 30, 2014.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Debt </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">F</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">inancing</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"> for AT&amp;T Transaction</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">On September </font><font style="display: inline;">17</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2014, the Company completed a registered debt offering of $775.0 million aggregate principal amount of 6.250% senior unsecured notes due 2021, and $775.0 million aggregate principal amount of 6.875% </font><font style="display: inline;">senior unsecured notes due 2025</font><font style="display: inline;">. The Company received net proceeds</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">after deducting underwriting fees</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">of $</font><font style="display: inline;">1,519.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million from the offering. The Company used the net proceeds from the sale of the notes, together with $350.0 million </font><font style="display: inline;">from the </font><font style="display: inline;">2014 CoBank Term Loan and cash on hand, to finance the AT&amp;T Transaction</font><font style="display: inline;"> that closed on October 24, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Pension Contributions</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Cash contributions to the pension plan were $39.3 million for the third quarter of 2014 and $70.5 million for</font><font style="display: inline;"> the first nine months of 2014. </font><font style="display: inline;">The Company made total </font><font style="display: inline;">cash </font><font style="display: inline;">contribution</font><font style="display: inline;">s to its pension plan </font><font style="display: inline;">for 2014 </font><font style="display: inline;">o</font><font style="display: inline;">f $</font><font style="display: inline;">83.2</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">million</font><font style="display: inline;">, including cash contributions of $</font><font style="display: inline;">12.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million on October 15, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Our 2014 pension contributions include the impact of the Highway and Transportation Funding Act of 2014. </font><font style="display: inline;">The Company believes that t</font><font style="display: inline;">here are no further </font><font style="display: inline;">required </font><font style="display: inline;">contributions to be made in 2014.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Non-GAAP Measures</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company uses certain non-GAAP financial measures in evaluating its performance. These include non-GAAP adjusted net income attributable to common shareholders of Frontier, free cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> operating cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;"> and adjusted operating cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;">. A reconciliation of the differences between non-GAAP adjusted net income attributable to common shareholders of Frontier, free cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> operating cash flow </font><font style="display: inline;">and adjusted operating cash flow </font><font style="display: inline;">and the most comparable financial measures calculated and presented in accordance with GAAP is included in the tables that follow.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">The non-GAAP financial measures are by definition not measures of financial performance under GAAP</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> and are not alternatives to operating income or net income attributable to common shareholders of Frontier as reflected in the statement of operations or to cash flow as reflected in the statement of cash flows</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> and are not necessarily indicative of cash available to fund all cash flow needs. The non-GAAP financial measures used by the Company may not be comparable to similarly titled measures of other companies.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">The Company believes that the presentation of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">these </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">non-GAAP financial measures provides useful information to investors regarding the Company&#x2019;s financial condition and results of operations because these measures, when used in conjunction with related GAAP financial measures, (i) together provide a more comprehensive view of the Company&#x2019;s core operations and ability to generate cash flow, (ii) provide investors with the financial analytical framework upon which management bases financial, operational, compensation and planning decisions and (iii) presents measurements that investors and rating agencies have indicated to management are useful to them in assessing the Company and its results of operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, the Company believes that non-GAAP adjusted net income attributable to common shareholders of Frontier, free cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">operating cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> and adjusted operating cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">, as the Company defines them, can assist in comparing performance from period to period, without taking into account factors affecting operating income or net income attributable to common shareholders of Frontier in the statement of operations, or cash flow reflected in the statement of cash flows, including changes in working capital and the timing of purchases and payments. The Company has shown adjustments to its financial presentations to exclude investment gains, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">certain </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">tax items, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">acquisition and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">integration costs, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">acquisition related interest expense, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">severance costs</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">pension settlement costs, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">non-cash pension and other postretirement benefit costs, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">losses on early extinguishment of debt</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> gain on sale of Mohave partnership interest</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> and gain</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;"> on sale of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">assets</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">as disclosed in the attached Schedules A and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">B</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">, because investors have indicated to management that such adjustments are useful to them in assessing the Company and its results of operations.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;">4</font>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 12pt"><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Management uses these non-GAAP financial measures to (i) assist in analyzing the Company&#x2019;s underlying financial performance from period to period, (ii) evaluate the financial performance of its business units, (iii) analyze and evaluate strategic and operational decisions, (iv) establish criteria for compensation decisions, and (v) assist management in understanding the Company&#x2019;s ability to generate cash flow and, as a result, to plan for future capital and operational decisions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Management uses these non-GAAP financial measures in conjunction with related GAAP financial measures.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">These non-GAAP financial measures have certain shortcomings.&nbsp;&nbsp;In particular, free cash flow does not represent the residual cash flow available for discretionary expenditures, since items such as debt repayments and dividends are not deducted in determining such measure. Operating cash flow has similar shortcomings as interest, income taxes, capital expenditures, debt repayments and dividends are not deducted in determining this measure.&nbsp;&nbsp;Management compensates for the shortcomings of these measures by utilizing them in conjunction with their comparable GAAP financial measures. The information in this press release should be read in conjunction with the financial statements and footnotes contained in our documents filed with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.</font>
		</p>

			<font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Frontier Communications Corporation (NASDAQ: FTR) offers broadband, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">voice, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">satellite video, wireless Internet data access, data security solutions, bundled offerings and specialized bundles for residential customers, small businesses and home offices, and advanced communications for medium and large businesses </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">in </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">2</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">8</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> states</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> including Connecticut</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;Frontier&#x2019;s </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">17,0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> employees</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, including the recently acquired Connecticut operations,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> are based entirely in the United States.&nbsp;&nbsp;More information is available at </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:underline;">www.frontier.com</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:underline;">www.frontier.com/ir</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>

			<font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Forward-Looking Statements</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">This press release contains forward-looking statements that are made pursuant to the safe harbor provisions of The Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. These statements are made on the basis of management&#x2019;s views and assumptions regarding future events and business performance. Words such as &#x201C;believe,&#x201D; &#x201C;anticipate,&#x201D; &#x201C;expect&#x201D; and similar expressions are intended to identify forward-looking statements. Forward-looking statements (including oral representations) involve risks and uncertainties that may cause actual results to differ materially from any future results, performance or achievements expressed or implied by such statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;These risks and uncertainties </font><font style="display: inline;">include, but are</font><font style="display: inline;"> not limited to</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">: &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">the ability to successfully integrate the Connecticut </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">operations </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">into our existing operations</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;"> and the diversion of management&#x2019;s attention from ongoing business and regular business responsibilities to effect such integration</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">; &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">the effects of increased expenses </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">or unanticipated liabilities </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">incurred due to activities related to the AT&amp;T Transaction; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">the risk that the cost savings from the AT&amp;T Transaction may not be fully realized; the sufficiency of the assets to be acquired from AT&amp;T to enable the combined company to operate </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">all aspects of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">the acquired business; disruption from the AT&amp;T Transaction making it more difficult to maintain relationships with customers or suppliers</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;"> of the Connecticut operations</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">; &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">our ability to meet </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">our debt and debt service obligations, which </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">have</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;"> increase</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">d as a result of</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;"> the AT&amp;T Transaction;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">the effects of greater than anticipated competition</font><font style="display: inline;"> from cable, wireless and other wireline carriers</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">that could require us to implement</font><font style="display: inline;"> new pricing, marketing strategies or new product or service offerings and the risk that we will not respond on a timely or profitable basis; reductions in the number of our voice customers that</font><font style="display: inline;"> we</font><font style="display: inline;"> cannot offset </font><font style="display: inline;">with</font><font style="display: inline;"> increases in broadband subscribers and sales of other products and services; our ability to maintain relationships with customers, employees or suppliers; the effects of ongoing changes in the regulation of the communications industry as a result of federal and state legislation and regulation, or changes in the enforcement or interpretation of such legislation and regulation; the effects of any unfavorable outcome with respect to any current or future legal, governmental or regulatory proceedings, audits or disputes; the effects of changes in the availability of federal and state universal </font><font style="display: inline;">service </font><font style="display: inline;">funding </font><font style="display: inline;">or other subsidies </font><font style="display: inline;">to us and our competitors; our ability to </font><font style="display: inline;">successfully </font><font style="display: inline;">adjust to changes in the communications industry and to implement strategies for growth; continued reductions in switched access revenues as a result of regulation, competition or technology substitutions; our ability to effectively manage service quality in our territories and meet mandated service quality metrics; our ability to successfully introduce new product offerings, including our ability to offer bundled service packages on terms that are both profitable to us and attractive to customers; </font><font style="display: inline;">the effects of </font><font style="display: inline;">changes in accounting policies or practices adopted voluntarily or as required by generally accepted accounting principles or regulations; our ability to effectively manage our operations, operating expenses and capital expenditures, and to repay, reduce or refinance our debt; the effects of changes in both general and local economic conditions on the markets that we serve, which can affect demand for our products and services, customer purchasing decisions, collectability of revenues and required levels of capital expenditures related to new construction of residences and businesses; the effects of technological changes and competition on our capital expenditures</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> product</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> and service offerings, including the lack of assurance that our network improvements</font><font style="display: inline;"> in speed and capacity</font><font style="display: inline;"> will be sufficient to meet or exceed the capabilities and quality of competing networks; the effects of increased medical</font><font style="display: inline;"> expenses (including as a result of the impact of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act) and</font><font style="display: inline;"> pension and postemployment expenses</font><font style="display: inline;">, such as retiree medical and severance costs,</font><font style="display: inline;"> and related funding requirements; </font><font style="display: inline;">the effects of </font><font style="display: inline;">changes in income tax rates, tax laws, regulations or rulings, or federal or state tax assessments; our ability to successfully renegotiate union contracts; changes in pension plan assumptions and/or the value of our pension plan assets</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> which could require us to make increased contributions to the pension plan </font><font style="display: inline;">in </font><font style="display: inline;">201</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;"> and</font><font style="display: inline;"> beyond; the effects of </font><font style="display: inline;">economic downturns</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">which could result in difficulty in collection of revenues and loss of customers; adverse changes in the credit markets or in the ratings given to our debt securities by nationally accredited ratings organizations, which could limit or restrict the availability, or increase the cost, of financing</font><font style="display: inline;"> to us</font><font style="display: inline;">; our cash flow from operations, amount of capital expenditures, debt service requirements, cash paid for income taxes and liquidity</font><font style="display: inline;"> may affect our payment of dividends on our common shares</font><font style="display: inline;">; the effects of state regulatory cash management practices that could limit our ability to transfer cash among our subsidiaries or dividend funds up to the parent company; and the effects of severe weather events such as hurricanes, tornadoes, ice storms or other natural or man-made disasters</font><font style="display: inline;">, which may increase our operating expenses or adversely impact customer revenue</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:SymbolMT;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">These and other uncertainties related to our business are described in greater detail in our filings with the </font><font style="display: inline;">U.S. </font><font style="display: inline;">Securities and Exchange Commission, including our reports on Forms 10-K and 10-Q, and the foregoing information should be read in conjunction with these filings.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not intend to update or revise these forward-looking statements to reflect the occurrence of future events or circumstances.</font>

			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">(</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">6</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">)</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:6pt;"> &nbsp;&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">Represents dividends paid divided by free cash flow, as defined in Schedule A.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.5pt;text-indent: -13.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Arial Unicode MS;font-size: 8pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Arial Unicode MS;font-size: 12pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.5pt;text-indent: -13.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Arial Unicode MS;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">(2</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">)</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:6pt;"> &nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">Reflects non-cash pension settlement charge of $40.3 million during the quarter and nine months ended September 30, 2013 for the accelerated recognition of a portion of the unrecognized actuarial losses in the Company&#x2019;s pension plan as a result of the significant level of lump sum retirement benefit payments made during 2013.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.5pt;text-indent: -13.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Arial Unicode MS;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">(</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">3</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">)</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%;font-size: 12pt;font-family:Arial Unicode MS;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 6.4pt 0pt 0pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">Excludes capital expenditures for integration activities.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.5pt;text-indent: -13.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Arial Unicode MS;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">(</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New 		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.5pt;text-indent: -13.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Arial Unicode MS;font-size: 12pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">(</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">5</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%">)</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;font-size:4pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%;font-size: 12pt;font-family:Arial Unicode MS;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 6.4pt 0pt 0pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">Excludes </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">acquisition and </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">integration costs, pension</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">/</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">OPEB costs (non-c</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">ash), </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">pension settlement costs, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">severance costs</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;"> and gain on sale of Mohave partnership interest</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8.5pt;">.</font>

		</p>
